[1] WHO update 5 Jan 2015
Date: Mon 5 Jan 2015
Source: Deutsche Welle [edited]
http://www.dw.de/ebola-death-toll-goes-past-8000-who/a-18172023


WHO: Ebola death toll goes past 8000
------------------------------------
The UN's health agency says the Ebola outbreak in West Africa has killed at least 8000 people. Sierra Leone had the biggest increase in fatalities since last week [28 Dec 2014 to 4 Jan 2015].

More than 8000 people have died in West Africa in the Ebola outbreak there, the World Health Organization (WHO) said on Mon [5 Jan 2015].

The WHO said that the 8153 deaths were among 20 656 known cases of the hemorrhagic fever in the 3 countries, representing a mortality rate of 39 percent. It said 2915 deaths had been reported from Sierra Leone, 3471 from Liberia and 1767 from Guinea. Sierra Leone had the largest rise in fatalities since the previous figures were issued on 2 Jan 2015, recording 88 deaths. [Only part of these figures have been confirmed. - Mod.JW]

Unconfirmed case in Berlin
--------------------------
Doctors in the German capital, Berlin, meanwhile said on Mon [5 Jan 2015] that a suspected Ebola infection in a patient from South Korea remains unconfirmed. The person, whose sex and age have not been named, was injured by a hypodermic needle while treating an Ebola patient in Sierra Leone and brought to Berlin for treatment on Sat [3 Jan 2015].

3 people infected with Ebola have so far been flown to Germany for treatment; 2 recovered, but a UN employee from Africa died in hospital in the eastern city of Leipzig.

UK nurse 'stable'
-----------------
Health Minister Jeremy Hunt told British parliamentarians Britain had tightened steps for dealing with possible Ebola patients after screening at London's Heathrow failed to detect the disease in the [Scottish] nurse. She contracted the disease while working at a British-built Ebola treatment center in Sierra Leone.

No more US screening for Malians
--------------------------------
The United States, for its part, has decided to drop extra Ebola screening for travelers coming to the country from Mali as of Tue [6 Jan 2015].

"Travelers from Mali will no longer be required to undergo enhanced screening and monitoring when entering the United States, nor will they be required to enter the country through the 5 designated airpots that perform this screening," the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention [CDC] said in a statement on Mon [5 Jan 2015].

On Tue [6 Jan 2015], Mali will have gone 42 days -- or 2 full incubation cycles -- since the last Ebola patient there had contact with anyone who was not wearing protective gear, the statement said.

Visitors from Guinea, Liberia and Sierra Leone remain subject to travel restrictions and monitoring.

